                                                                            <comments>
                            <comment id="27519" author="pjones" created="Fri, 27 Jan 2012 17:49:07 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;This is believed to be fixed in 1.8.7. Please reopen if it reoccurs with 1.8.7&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="26863" author="yujian" created="Wed, 18 Jan 2012 23:55:46 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Hi Chris,&lt;br/&gt;
From the Maloo report, I saw the b1_8 build was &lt;a href=&quot;http://build.lab.whamcloud.com/job/lustre-b1_8/100&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;http://build.lab.whamcloud.com/job/lustre-b1_8/100&lt;/a&gt;, which was Lustre 1.8.6-wc1. &lt;a href=&quot;https://jira.whamcloud.com/browse/LU-544&quot; title=&quot;1.8&amp;lt;-&amp;gt;2.1 interop: conf-sanity test 56: mkfs.lustre FAIL: Journal size too big for filesystem.&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;LU-544&quot;&gt;&lt;del&gt;LU-544&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt; was fixed after that release.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Since we always test the interop between the latest b1_8 release and 2.x release, could you please update the autotest system to use Lustre 1.8.7-wc1 release build &lt;a href=&quot;http://newbuild.whamcloud.com/job/lustre-b1_8/150/&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;http://newbuild.whamcloud.com/job/lustre-b1_8/150/&lt;/a&gt; ? Thanks!&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="26783" author="niu" created="Wed, 18 Jan 2012 01:29:16 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Looks it&apos;s duplicated with &lt;a href=&quot;https://jira.whamcloud.com/browse/LU-544&quot; title=&quot;1.8&amp;lt;-&amp;gt;2.1 interop: conf-sanity test 56: mkfs.lustre FAIL: Journal size too big for filesystem.&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;LU-544&quot;&gt;&lt;del&gt;LU-544&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt;:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;We are making filesystem with 16M journal size on a ~39M mds device, why the mds size is so small? Yujian/Chris, could you take a look? Thanks.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="26781" author="niu" created="Wed, 18 Jan 2012 01:12:11 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Hi, Chris&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Could you take a look to see why the mkfs for /dev/lvm-MDS/P0 on fat-intel-3vm7 failed? Thanks.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="26780" author="niu" created="Wed, 18 Jan 2012 00:09:12 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;The debug log shows&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div class=&quot;code panel&quot; style=&quot;border-width: 1px;&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;codeContent panelContent&quot;&gt;
&lt;pre class=&quot;code-java&quot;&gt;== conf-sanity test 56: check big indexes == 16:39:05 (1326760745)
fat-intel-3vm7: 
fat-intel-3vm7: mkfs.lustre FATAL: Unable to build fs /dev/lvm-MDS/P0 (256)
fat-intel-3vm7: 
fat-intel-3vm7: mkfs.lustre FATAL: mkfs failed 256

   Permanent disk data:
Target:     lustre-MDTffff
Index:      unassigned
Lustre FS:  lustre
Mount type: ldiskfs
Flags:      0x75
              (MDT MGS needs_index first_time update )
Persistent mount opts: errors=remount-ro,iopen_nopriv,user_xattr,acl
Parameters: sys.timeout=20

device size = 29596MB
formatting backing filesystem ldiskfs on /dev/lvm-MDS/P0
	target name  lustre-MDTffff
	4k blocks     10000
	options       -J size=16 -I 512 -i 2048 -q -O dirdata,uninit_bg,dir_nlink,huge_file,flex_bg -E lazy_journal_init -F
mkfs_cmd = mke2fs -j -b 4096 -L lustre-MDTffff -J size=16 -I 512 -i 2048 -q -O dirdata,uninit_bg,dir_nlink,huge_file,flex_bg -E lazy_journal_init -F /dev/lvm-MDS/P0 10000
   
   Journal size too big &lt;span class=&quot;code-keyword&quot;&gt;for&lt;/span&gt; filesystem.
&lt;/pre&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The mkfs for mds device failed, I think it should be testing environment problem.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="26706" author="pjones" created="Tue, 17 Jan 2012 08:58:16 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Niu&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Could you please look into this one?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Thanks&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Peter&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
